---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import ExperienceSection from '../components/ExperienceSection.astro';
---

<Base title="Ismael Duran · Personal Site">
  <main>
    <header>
      <div class="name-row">
        {/* Portrait cropped from ps_image.heic (dusk shot on campus) to a clean
            head-and-shoulders square, exported web-ready. alt="" is intentional:
            the adjacent h1 already names me, so a decorative photo avoids a
            screen reader announcing the name twice (mirrors the logo marks in
            ExperienceSection). */}
        <img
          class="avatar"
          src="/me.jpg"
          alt=""
          width="88"
          height="88"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <h1>Ismael Duran</h1>
      </div>
      <p class="contact-row">
        <span>iaredur@stanford.edu</span>
        <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
        <span>(210)-974-1161</span>
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="tldr">
      <h2 class="section-heading">TL;DR</h2>
      <ul class="tldr-list">
        <li>
          Finished my third year at Stanford, and I'm after a paid
          contract/internship role for the early fall
        </li>
        <li>
          I aspire to be a well-rounded engineer in the spaces of hardware,
          software, and AI
        </li>
        <li>
          Please go ahead and look into my work history and project details to
          see if anything aligns
        </li>
        <li>
          I can play many roles if I have to. I can go all the way from bare
          metal, code, and execution to strategy, leadership, and growth
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <div class="sections-grid">
      <div class="section-column">
        <ExperienceSection
          title="Work History"
          inGrid
          entries={[
            {
              image: '/experiences/amazon-mark.png',
              name: 'Amazon Lab126',
              role: 'HDE Intern',
              meta: '2025',
              bullets: [
                'Amazon is creating a foldable device and I was tasked to predict visible crease on foldable phones',
                'Experimented with 3 Samsung foldable phones to understand crease patterns through repeated folding-cycles and closed-state timed measurements. I did this in contiguous sets increasing the amount of cycles each time, then measured the changing width and depth using a laser-microscope',
                'Built a small dataset with this data and trained a model using mean squared error loss to predict how much usage it takes to see visible crease',
              ],
            },
            {
              image: '/experiences/amazon-mark.png',
              name: 'Amazon Lab126',
              role: 'HDE Intern',
              meta: '2024',
              bullets: [
                "Amazon's Echo Buds were getting many negative reviews and I was tasked to understand why and find a solution",
                "After obtaining access to every review, I vectorized the dataset and ran top-k means to pinpoint an issue to fix. The ear-tip getting stuck on customer ears was the bud's biggest pain point",
                'To find the earbud spec, I built a dataset with an Instron machine and trained a regression-based model to predict the minimum retention force the ear-tip needed to hold',
              ],
            },
            {
              image: '/experiences/jane-mark.png',
              name: 'Jane Street',
              role: 'Unboxed Fellow',
              meta: '2023',
              bullets: [
                'Invited to join an intensive three-week hybrid program where Jane Street traders taught SQL, combinatorics, and ETF trading',
                'Received a $2,000 scholarship toward school expenses',
              ],
            },
            {
              image: '/experiences/renu-mark.png',
              name: 'Renu Robotics',
              role: 'Engineering Intern',
              meta: '2023',
              bullets: [
                'Built a ROS2 python pipeline that would stream sensor data from various components on the robot, clean it using message filters, and portray it on an html site',
                'Verified my code by manually driving around a robot outside the office',
              ],
            },
          ]}
        />

        <Section
          title="ML Stuff"
          inGrid
          entries={[
            {
              title: 'Sample-Efficient Reinforcement Learning for Video Agents',
              href: 'https://github.com/DonIsmaelito/VideoAgent-RL',
              bullets: [
                'I started from the question of whether an agent can understand a full video while watching as little of it as possible, and built an experiment that uses different sample-efficient reinforcement learning algorithms to teach an agent when to stop watching and which tools to call next, rather than following a strict tool-based harness. Then evaluated each algorithm',
                'Built a reinforcement learning environment where each episode gave the agent one video question, a bank with size 32 CLIP frame embedding blocks from the video, and eight possible actions for retrieving relevant frames, adjusting the search window, requesting BLIP-2 captions, or answering',
                'Designed the agent’s state to track the question, evidence collected so far, current search window, previous tool usage, and remaining call budget',
                'Implemented a score function where the agent earned one point for a correct answer and lost 0.03 points per tool call',
                'Built a python pipeline that used T4 GPUs for CLIP/BLIP-2 inference, trained RL controllers on cached features in CPU containers, and parallelized experiments. Spent around 40 bucks on Modal credits',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'FPGA FlashAttention Kernel',
              href: 'https://github.com/DonIsmaelito/flashattention_kernel',
              bullets: [
                'I wanted to learn about recent transformer optimizations, so I built FlashAttention from scratch as an FPGA kernel in SystemC, compiled to RTL for an FPGA on AWS F2',
                'Following the FlashAttention paper, I never compute the full N×N attention score matrix, I streamed it as 32×32 query and key tiles through an online softmax update, so the kernel only holds one tile plus a small max sum on-chip',
                'To use the FPGA benefits, I built 16 parallel processing elements that each handle one query row with a 64-wide dot product per cycle and used 16-bit fixed point with wider 24/32-bit accumulators for the attention math',
                'Built a python CPU baseline and the kernel had a 73x speedup over it',
              ],
            },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="section-column">
        <Section
          title="Apps"
          inGrid
          entries={[
            {
              title: 'Peck',
              href: 'https://peck.insforge.site',
              bullets: [
                'Current side project',
                'A gamified mobile app that turns data labeling into quick, one-minute game levels. As your dataset grows, you can easily access it with an API call',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'Clippa',
              href: 'https://clippa.app',
              bullets: [
                'Built a web app that lets users turn their multi-hour streams into edited TikTok-style clips in under 3 minutes for free',
                "Built a Python pipeline that takes a raw mp4 or a YouTube link, pulls the transcript straight from YouTube's captions for free (or runs a small ASR model on the ffmpeg-extracted audio when there aren't any), then hands the transcript to a large reasoning model that reads it in a single pass to pick the moments",
                'Originally, the pipeline took around 8 minutes to process 10 clips. I was able to do a 62% time reduction by fetching transcripts/video concurrently and rendering clips in parallel with ffmpeg’s veryfast preset',
                'Built a live Twitch Top-100 grid where every visitor shares one cached call to Twitch instead of each browser hitting the API so it plays fast and smooth on my site',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'Holdem-AI',
              href: 'https://holdem-ai.com',
              bullets: [
                'Built a web app that lets people play NLH against 5 AI models (Claude, ChatGPT, Grok, Gemini, and DeepSeek) solo or in multiplayer tables',
                'Built the multiplayer feature using an open-source node server framework (Colyseus) that handled real-time syncing and game updates',
                "Built the context and action system for each poker bot in Python. Before a model acts, it's given its equity, pot odds, outs, position, and a short read on how each opponent has been playing. It outputs a legal poker move as its action",
              ],
            },
          ]}
        />

        <Section
          title="Agents"
          inGrid
          entries={[
            {
              title: 'Watch Agent',
              href: '/p/watchagent',
              bullets: [
                'Built a 6 tool video-understanding agent harness that lets and orchestrator inspect video, audio, and transcript to find exact query moments cheaply',
                'Benchmarked the harness on long-form subsets of Video-MME, WorldQA, and EgoSchema, beating agent systems built on gpt-sized models',
                'Built a python evaluation pipeline using a rented CPU container and H100 container from modal. The CPU worker grabs a fixed batch of videos + q/a from the benchmark on HuggingFace and runs the harness, which calls Qwen from a separate H100 container via vLLM',
                'My harness ‘watched’ over 500 videos and answered more than a 1,000 questions all under 100 bucks of Modal credits',
                'Wrote a detailed report about the project',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'Co-Scientist',
              href: 'https://www.loom.com/share/566403785fef4f2785e300bfc5880bd2',
              bullets: [
                'Along with two other peers, we built a deep-research agent leveraging a multi-agent system architecture. A principal investigator agent would receive the query, and spin up N specialized agents to tackle the research plan created by the PI. Each of these agents obtained technical context from Arxiv and Pubmed APIs',
                'I built the context pipelines that would call these APIs, find the relevant papers, and clean the large batch of tokens by stripping abstracts, relevant work, and citations using regex. This minimized 35% of agent token input',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'MedMinute',
              href: 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/14G-TwpP49-4w6Uy0CuSLGhijgDdDIPmY/view?usp=vids_web',
              bullets: [
                'MedMinute is a local form filling platform where people can talk, type, or pull from existing PDFs to complete blank medical forms',
                "I built a Python pipeline that takes a PDF or image, runs OCR using pdf2image and Tesseract, chunks the extracted text, embeds it with Ollama's embed text model into a local Chroma vector database, extracts patient information as JSON using an LLM, and then maps that information onto blank form fields so the frontend can update them live",
                'I added a voice path where the browser records microphone audio and streams it over a FastAPI WebSocket, ElevenLabs transcribes the speech, an LLM generates a reply, and ElevenLabs converts that reply back to speech for the user',
              ],
            },
            {
              title: 'Doxxing-Detection Bot',
              href: 'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1gKbbb8InGe5QK673eAH69f6UzZwnb_nc/view?usp=sharing',
              bullets: [
                'With some friends, we built a Discord trust & safety feature that detects doxxing within a channel and applies consequences automatically given their magnitude',
                'Integrated Supabase to store and monitor channel activity. Every message then goes through a regex pass, and if flagged, it gets removed automatically and goes to an LLM for review',
              ],
            },
          ]}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
  main {
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: clamp(3rem, 12vh, 9rem) 1.5rem 4rem;
    min-height: 100vh;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  header {
    padding-top: 1.25rem;
    padding-bottom: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  /* Centered identity row. Balanced vertical padding uses the space left by the
     removed social tagline and seats the portrait/name slightly lower. */
  .name-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: clamp(0.9rem, 2.5vw, 1.25rem);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .contact-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    color: #fff;
  }

  /* Circular head-and-shoulders portrait, sized a hair taller than the wordmark
     and scaling with it. object-fit: cover centers the square source;
     flex-shrink:0 stops the circle squashing when a long name wraps on narrow
     screens; the 1px ring gives definition on both paper and dark backgrounds. */
  .avatar {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: clamp(64px, 13vw, 92px);
    height: clamp(64px, 13vw, 92px);
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: var(--surface);
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 8vw, 4rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.05;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* TL;DR band — breaks out to the same width as the columns band below, so the
     single-column bullet sentences stretch across the full width and use the
     space instead of leaving the right side blank. Centered on the same axis as
     the columns band; on small viewports the band clamp makes it full-width. */
  .tldr {
    --band: min(var(--measure-wide), 100vw - 3rem);
    width: var(--band);
    margin-inline: calc(50% - var(--band) / 2);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 2.5rem;
  }

  /* Dash-marked bullets in the page's serif body voice: full-contrast text with
     a muted em-dash marker, hung in a 1.6rem gutter so wrapped lines align. */
  .tldr-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.65rem;
  }

  .tldr-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 1.6rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .tldr-list li::before {
    content: '–';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  /* Nested sub-list under a TL;DR point (the "currently interested in" items).
     A dotted marker, slightly muted, indented under the parent point. */
  .tldr-sublist {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0.55rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.4rem;
  }

  .tldr-sublist li {
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .tldr-sublist li::before {
    content: '·';
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  /* ---- Columns band ----
     <main> is capped at --measure (68ch), and a normal child can't exceed that
     box — so this ONE band escapes main's content box to breathe.

     --band is the target width: as wide as --measure-wide but never
     wider than the viewport minus main's 1.5rem L/R padding, so there is never
     a horizontal scrollbar on small screens. (--measure-wide is a plain length,
     not min(…,100%), specifically so this isn't re-clamped to main's box.)

     margin-inline: calc(50% - --band/2) recentres the band on main's centre
     axis — the same axis the viewport is centred on — so header/intro prose
     stays put at 68ch while the columns spread wider. When --band can't exceed
     main's box (small viewports) the calc is ~0 and it degrades to a normal
     full-width child. A short accent divider sits above the columns (see
     ::before); columns are borderless (Section `inGrid`) and top-aligned. */
  .sections-grid {
    --band: min(var(--measure-wide), 100vw - 3rem);
    width: var(--band);
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    margin-inline: calc(50% - var(--band) / 2);
    position: relative;
    padding-top: 2.5rem;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    column-gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  /* Each desktop column flows independently, so a shorter Apps section no
     longer inherits the height of Work History before ML Stuff can begin. */
  .section-column {
    min-width: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 4rem;
  }

  /* Short divider above the columns band — replaces the old full-width hairline
     with a brief, centered accent rule between the TL;DR and the columns.
     Absolutely positioned so it stays out of the grid flow; color-mixed a touch
     stronger than the faint hairline so the short segment reads clearly. */
  .sections-grid::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    width: 7rem;
    height: 1px;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--text-muted) 45%, transparent);
  }

  @media (max-width: 54rem) {
    .sections-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 4rem;
    }

    .section-column {
      gap: 4rem;
    }
  }
</style>
